{:spec/title "Polylith compliance remediation (pass 2) — fix remaining poly check errors"

 :spec/description
 "Fix all remaining `poly check` errors after the Error 101 interface-bypass
  pass. Structural Polylith fixes only — no behavior changes.

  GROUP 1: Complete interface definitions (Error 103 — 2 sites)
  phase-deployment and phase-software-factory both claim to implement the
  `phase` interface but are missing ~28 functions each. For each missing
  function, either:
  (a) add a pass-through in the component's interface.clj that delegates
      to the same impl as the canonical `phase` component, OR
  (b) restructure so these components extend the phase interface instead
      of claiming to fully implement it (Polylith extension pattern).

  Option (a) is simpler; option (b) is architecturally cleaner if most
  functions genuinely belong to the canonical phase component.

  GROUP 2: Resolve multi-impl interfaces (Error 106 × 6, Error 108 × 1)

  *** IMPORTANT: Components must NEVER overload the same interface name. ***

  The correct pattern (per ixi's tool-pubsub / adapter-pubsub and LLM
  protocols): each component has a UNIQUE interface name. Runtime backend
  selection happens via multimethod dispatch inside a canonical interface
  component, or via adapter components that each expose their own distinct
  interface.

  Reference pattern from ixi:
    components/tool-pubsub/.../interface.clj   — canonical interface
    components/tool-pubsub/.../extensibility.clj — (defmulti publish! ...)
    components/tool-pubsub-coreasync/          — interface name: :tool-pubsub-coreasync
    components/adapter-pubsub-gcp/             — interface name: :adapter-pubsub

  None of those components share an interface name. Swapping is done by
  choosing which adapter is included, or by registering a backend method
  against the canonical multimethod.

  For `data-foundry` interface (22 components in dev):
    - Give each component a unique interface name (e.g., :connector-auth,
      :connector-retry, :connector-github — NOT :data-foundry)
    - Promote one component to the canonical `:data-foundry` interface
      that owns any shared multimethods for cross-backend dispatch
    - Projects then include whichever concrete components they need, each
      under its own interface name — no overload

  For `phase` interface (3 components):
    - `phase` stays canonical (:phase) and owns any dispatch multimethods
    - `phase-software-factory` gets its own interface (e.g., :phase-software-factory)
    - `phase-deployment` gets its own interface (e.g., :phase-deployment)
    - Projects include whichever they need; no two components claim :phase

  Do NOT use Polylith profiles to work around interface overload — profiles
  are for bundling dev/test variants, not for swapping implementations of
  the same interface name. The fix is to rename interfaces, not to profile
  the conflict away.

  GROUP 3: Complete project definitions (Error 107 × 3)
  miniforge project: add mcp-context-server base
  miniforge-core: add diagnosis, improvement, reliability components
  miniforge-tui: add 10 missing components + 2 missing bases

  Each project's deps.edn needs the missing entries. Verify the actual
  runtime reachability — some may genuinely not be needed and the poly
  check should be suppressed instead.

  GROUP 4: Fix base-to-brick direct dep (Error 112)
  bases/mcp-context-server/deps.edn has `../../components/messages` as
  a direct path. Change to rely on the component's interface-level
  dependency graph like other bases.

  GROUP 5: Clean up warnings (202, 205, 207)
  - Warning 202: Remove missing paths from development project deps.edn,
    or create the missing directories if they should exist.
  - Warning 205: Rename test fixture namespaces or configure poly to
    exclude them from brick scanning.
  - Warning 207: Remove unreachable components from project deps.edn
    (24 + 14 + 13 entries total)."

